{
  "result": "At dawn, the city is briefly honest. Delivery trucks rumble like old dogs clearing their throats, and streetlights blink out one by one, surrendering to a pale sky. I like this hour because nothing performs yet. Storefront windows are mirrors instead of invitations, and even the billboards seem shy, their colors muted by fog.\n\nA baker on the corner props open his door, and warm air spills onto the sidewalk like a secret. Across the street, a woman waters stubborn plants in chipped ceramic pots, whispering to them as if negotiations might persuade roots to deepen. Somewhere above, a radio crackles with last night\u2019s game highlights, sounding both triumphant and tired.\n\nBy seven, the masks return. Coffee cups become shields, headphones become walls, and everyone resumes the brisk choreography of purpose. But for a few soft minutes, the city feels less like a machine and more like a village that remembers itself. You can hear individual footsteps, identify laughter from a single open window, smell oranges being sliced in a kitchen three floors up.\n\nI think that\u2019s why I walk early whenever I can: to witness the moment before momentum. It reminds me that beneath schedules, deadlines, and fluorescent urgency, ordinary life is still handmade\u2014kneaded, watered, whispered, brewed. Morning doesn\u2019t erase the world\u2019s troubles, but it does offer a small, daily rehearsal for hope. If I miss it, the day still happens, of course, but I feel late to my own life as though I arrived after the note.",
